entry.title: Reflect font-size-adjust to FontCacheKey.
entry.content:
The current FontCacheKey does not care about font-size-adjust.

This results in inappropriate font data returned and texts with

'font-face: size-adjust' under the same font-family name are rendered

in an incorrectly adjusted size. When we look up cached fonts,

we generate a FontCacheKey based on the given font description in

CSSSegmentedFontFace::GetFontData(). Unfortunately, the key generation

logic (i.e., FontDescriptioin::CacheKey()) does not care about

font-size-adjust, and texts under the same font-family name get

the same cached font data regardless of font-size-adjust used.

As a result, @font-face: size-adjust is ignored for the texts

as they have font-size-adjust.



A fix is to make FontCacheKey reflect font-size-adjust.



Test: external/wpt/css/css-fonts/size-adjust-03.html

entry.title: [Autofill] Fix filling fields in shadow DOM
entry.content:
Consider the structure



# shadow DOM



# shadow DOM





Before this CL, triggering Autofill from this field was a no-op.



AutofillAgent first compared the 's associated form's

FormRendererId to the filling data's FormRendererId. These are not

equal: the former is null, the latter is 's FormRendererId.



Therefore, AutofillAgent tried to find the WebFormControlElement

that corresponds to . That search, however, does not find

because it only finds

- unassociated form controls in the main DOM

- fields that are owned by (i.e., associated to or shadow-DOM

descendants of) a form element in the main DOM,

neither of which is the case here.



This CL fixes the issue by introducing GetOwningForm(), which for

an unassociated WebFormControlElement falls back to the

shadow-DOM-including ancestors.

entry.title: [Extensions] Don't allow user scripts to message other extensions

User scripts should only be able to message their own corresponding

extension, not other extensions. Enforce this in the renderer, and

validate these expectations in the browser by terminating the renderer

if a message is attempted.

UserScriptWorldBrowserTest) and to guard against an exploit (in

extension_security_exploit_browsertest.cc), in addition to targeted

unittests.



In order to make user script world testing easier, also expose the

chrome.test API to these contexts. This is only available in test

environments.

entry.title: Suppress ACTION_CALL if there is no dialer.
entry.content:
The change

- queries PackageManager to verify whether there is any activity

capable of processing ACTION_DIAL,

- drops the extraneous check for Omnibox Action placement on the

suggestions list (already handled by https://crrev.com/c/4402397)



The change is short of a few tests to offer full coverage - however

offering proper coverage would be less beneficial than addressing the

tech debt *and then* adding the tests.



The debt that needs to be addressed is how OmniboxActions are

constructed and what their responsibilities are. We should not be

creating ACTION_CALL items in the first place if the dialer is not

available, and for that we must migrate some of the logic to

OmniboxActionInSuggest, at a minimum make the Context accessible.

entry.title: [ScrollUnif.] Let EnsureCompositorScrollNode not depend on transform
entry.content:
When there is a fixed-position element containing a scroller, the

scroll tree and the transform tree have different hierarchies. There

is not a good way to find the scroll translation node (in the

transform tree) of the parent of a scroll node under the

fixed-position element.



To avoid the problem, this CL lets PropertyTreeManager::

EnsureCompositorScrollNode() not depend on scroll translation.

After ensuring all scroll nodes (including painted composited,

painted non-composited, unpainted), we update transform related

fields of the scroll nodes for all painted scroll translations.

entry.title: FLEDGE: Enable screen height as unit and pure numbers input for ad
entry.content:
size.



Currently, for generateBid() and joinAdInterestGroup(), the supported

ad size units are

* "px": pixel

* "sw": screen width



This CL adds the unit:

* "sh": screen height



The parser is also updated to support parsing pure numbers as pixels.

For example, "100" is parsed as 100 pixels.



A regular expression is used to match the input, and capture the

sub-patterns for value and unit.

^\s*((?:0|(?:[1-9][0-9]*))(?:\.[0-9]+)?)(px|sw|sh)?\s*$



It basically means we match

1. Zero or more leading spaces.

2. Numbers, with optionally decimal point and digits. No leading space, cannot begin with zero, non-negative. (Sub-pattern captured)

3. Immediately followed by an unit which can be one of "px", "sw" or "sh", or the unit can be ignored entirely.
